Reminder: it is more important who you sign up with and listen to for colour analysis content rather than focussing on whether in person vs virtual is correct. Here are the things I recommend looking for when deciding a colour analysis professional to work with and listen to in content: 1) Accredited in person colour analysis training 2) Vast in person colour analysis experience 3) Client feedback after client has tried out colours for a bit (includes perhaps before and afters in their best hair, makeup, clothing colours) 4) Virtual colour analysis client feedback (if signing up for virtual service) 5) Ensuring you are happy with their colour analysis system used - eg in my opinion a 4 season system is not refined enough for everyone. Yay True Deep for this virtual colour analysis client! True Deep is the palette that rests exactly midway between Autumn and Winter. Many who are Deep Autumn or Deep Winter in the colour analysis system I use are confused why they also receive a Deep referenceâ€¦ that is because your colouring is also in harmony with the Deep palette qualities. For a Deep Winter or Deep Autumn who chooses handheld references, I do suggest getting a Winter  or Autumn add-on card (if appropriate, given you are ordering anyways, add-on cards are relatively very inexpensive), but ultimately the colours on the add-on card will not be as good as the Deep colours on Deep Winters or Deep Autumns as the Deep palette brings in qualities of both seasons (which Deep Autumns and Deep Winters also require for colour analysis checks). Add-on card colours when suggested are usually only recommended as accents or for smaller details in looks.
